# Secret Shuttle Agent Instructions

Use Secret Shuttle whenever this repository or task needs API keys, tokens, webhook secrets, env vars, production credentials, generated secrets, or secret values.

Setup:

```bash
npx secret-shuttle init
```

Run this once per project. `init` spawns the daemon, walks the user through setting a vault passphrase via a local browser window (the CLI never reads the passphrase), and auto-installs this agent's canonical skill file. After `init` succeeds the agent is ready to use the Burst 5+ verb surface (`provision`, `secrets list`, `audit`, etc.).

Rules:

- Never ask the user to paste raw secrets into chat.
- Never print, log, summarize, screenshot, or expose raw secret values.
- Use refs like `ss://stripe/prod/STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET`.
- Use normal browser tooling only for navigation.
- When a secret is visible or about to be entered, stop observing the page.
- While blind mode is active, do not use screenshots, DOM inspection, accessibility-tree reads, console reads, network-body reads, or clipboard reads.
- Prefer `secret-shuttle provision` (the magic path) — it provisions a whole project's secrets, or a single `--secret`, in one approval and drives any needed capture/inject internally.
- Use `secret-shuttle provision --secret <NAME> --from random_32_bytes` for new local secrets.
- For a secret revealed on a page, mark the controls with `secret-shuttle browser mark focused --as <label>` / `browser mark pick --as <label>`, then run `secret-shuttle reveal-capture` (it manages blind mode, captures the value, and hides it — you never see it).
- To write a secret into a focused field and submit, mark the field and submit control, then run `secret-shuttle inject-submit` (it injects, clicks submit, verifies a success marker, and auto-resumes only if the secret is proven gone).
- Verify production setup using non-secret UI signals only (success text, audit summaries via `secret-shuttle audit`, ref fingerprints via `secret-shuttle secrets get-ref`).
- Approve production actions in the Secret Shuttle window your browser opens — there is no CLI flag that bypasses approval.

Common flow (the magic path — one approval, capture + inject handled for you):

```bash
secret-shuttle provision \
  --secret STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET \
  --from capture --url https://dashboard.stripe.com/webhooks \
  --to vercel:production
```

Lower-level transactions, when you need to drive capture/inject yourself.
First start the daemon-controlled browser and mark the relevant controls:

```bash
secret-shuttle browser start

# Reveal a secret on a page: mark the reveal control + the revealed field,
# then capture (blind mode is managed inside reveal-capture — no manual blind start):
secret-shuttle browser mark pick --as reveal-btn
secret-shuttle browser mark focused --as revealed-field
secret-shuttle reveal-capture \
  --name STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET \
  --env production \
  --source stripe \
  --reveal-handle reveal-btn \
  --field-handle revealed-field \
  --allow-domain dashboard.stripe.com

# Write a secret into a field and submit: mark the field + submit control,
# then inject-submit (verifies a success marker, auto-resumes only if proven gone):
secret-shuttle browser mark focused --as api-key-field
secret-shuttle browser mark pick --as save-button
secret-shuttle inject-submit \
  --ref ss://stripe/prod/STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET \
  --field-handle api-key-field \
  --submit-handle save-button \
  --success-text "Saved"
```

To hand a secret to an external binary, use a template instead of arbitrary commands:

```bash
secret-shuttle template run vercel-env-add \
  --ref ss://stripe/prod/STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET \
  --param name=STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET \
  --param environment=production
```
